<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title></title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">WWC0010</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:15pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:15pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:15pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:15pt; font-weight:bold">submitted by Teach First </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Contents</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">Introduction</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">Headline View</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">s</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">Findings</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">Question 1: What is the extent of white working class pupils’ educational underachievement?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">Question 2: What factors do you think are responsible for white working class pupils’ educational underachievement?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">Question 3: Is the problem of educational underachievement particularly worse for boys or girls?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">Question 4: What steps can schools take to improve the educational outcomes and attainment of white working class pupils?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">Question 5: What role can government play in delivering improved educational outcomes for white working class pupils?</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">Conclusion</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">Appendix</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.7pt; padding-left:2.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">Teach First is pleased to respond to the Education Select Committee’s inquiry into the educational achievement of white working class pupils, an inquiry that closely aligns with our vision that no child’s educational success should be limited by their socio-economic background. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">Over recent years, educational inequality has risen up the political agenda, leading to Teach First being named as one of the most prestigious career choices for top graduates in the UK, and a number of successful initiatives including the London challenge. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.7pt; padding-left:2.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">Despite significant inroads being made to tackle educational inequality, ed</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">ucation across the country continues to be a postcode lottery for children from poorer families. Indeed, </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">the achievement gap between children from poorer families and their wealthier peers remains stubbornly wide with just </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">over a third of young people receiving free-school meals achieving five </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">GCSEs A*-C compared to just over two-thirds of all other pupils</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">Not only is this manifestly unfair, they also show that young talent is being wasted on an industrial scale. However, as research suggests, the prevalence of educational inequality is particularly apparent among white working class pupils. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.7pt; padding-left:2.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">Last year for instance, less than a third of white British students eligible for free school meals reached the national GCSE target of 5 A*-C passes (including English and maths) compared to double that amount for white children from wealthier backgrounds. </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">As studies show, no other ethnic group has such a large gap between its poorer and wealthier pupils. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.7pt; padding-left:2.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">In order to assess the extent of educational inequality that white working class pupils experience, we asked a small number (22) of our participants (</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">teachers undertaking the two-year Leadership Development Programme with Teach First)</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt"> and ambassadors (alumni) to respond to a survey that included the following questions: </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">What is the extent of white working class pupils’ educational underachievement?</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">What factors do you think are responsible for white working class pupils’ educational underachievement?</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">Is the problem of educational underachievement particularly worse for boys or girls?</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">What steps can schools take to improve the educational outcomes and attainment of white working class pupils?</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">What role can government play in delivering improved educational outcomes for white working class pupils?</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.7pt; padding-left:2.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">Our teachers work, for a minimum of two years, in primary and secondary schools where </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">more than half of pupils come from the poorest 30% of families in the UK, according to the IDACI (Income Deprivation Affecting Children Index). Therefore, the small sample of participants and ambassadors whose response make up this response have experienced first-hand the prevalence of educational inequality among children from disadvantaged backgrounds and are familiar with some the barriers that they face.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.7pt; padding-left:2.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">Whilst their individual views do not necessarily reflect the views of Teach First as an organisation, we</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt"> hope that our contribution is helpful to the Education Select Committee’s inquiry. We would be more than happy to discuss these findings further in front of the committee, as well as provide additional information from Teach First’s experience.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">For more information, please contact Will Staynes, Press &amp; Public Affairs Officer via </span><a href="mailto:WStaynes@teachfirst.org.uk"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">WStaynes@teachfirst.org.uk</span></a><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Headline Views</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.7pt; padding-left:2.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">Overall, respondents to our survey generally agreed that white working class children experience a greater level of educational disadvantage than working class pupils from other ethnicities. This, however, is unlikely to be driven by ethnicity alone – with local economic, historical and geographic factors taking </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">precedenc</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">. </span><br /><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">When asked to state three of the main reasons as to why white working class pupils experience a particular level of educational disadvantage, lack of home support, limited history of family members achieving in education , and deprivation in the area were cited as the main reasons for why there is a greater sense of educational disadvantage. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">Participants and ambassadors were broadly in agreement as to what governments can do to improve educational outcomes for white working class pupils. These can be broken down into three key themes, principally: more work to encourage white working class parents to have and support higher aspirations for their children; more targeted support for children from white working class backgrounds; and encouraging a greater use of social and community capital amongst children from white working class pupils. </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">These reasons given, and the broader experience of Teach First, recognise that white working class children are not a homogenous group.  </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">The challenges they face vary greatly and are often driven by geographical and economic factors, rather than ethnicity. For example, within London </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">almost half of London’s poorest white pupils get five good GCSEs with English and maths compared with the national average of 31% for white children on Free School Meals</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Main Findings</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">What is the extent of white working class pupils’ educational underachievement?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.7pt; padding-left:2.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">Of those that responded to our survey, all agreed that white working class pupils experience educational disadvantage. 85% of respondents agreed that white working class children experience a greater level of educational disadvantage than working class pupils from other ethnicities. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.7pt; padding-left:2.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">Based on their own experiences of working in schools in disadvantaged communities, respondent gave the following reasons for disparity between working class children from different ethnicities:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">A lack of specific interventions for white working class pupils, compared to those that are available for children from ethnic minority backgrounds – like EAL services within schools for instance.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">A greater prevalence of intergenerational poverty and unemployment compared to other ethnicities - particularly in areas outside of large urban centres where industry is in decline and there are high levels of under or unemployment. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">Parents and children often felt resigned to their status as ‘working class’.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">Other suggestions included the sense that white working class people are often held back by others’ misconceptions, resulting in a general lack of self-confidence, as well as a lack of parental support, and a limited understanding of higher education.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">What factors do you think are responsible for white working class pupils’ educational underachievement?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">Overall, the reasons given by participants and ambassadors for the educational disadvantage of white working class pupils were broadly mixed. </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">However, lack of home support, limited history of family members achieving in education, and deprivation in their areas were cited as the main reasons for why there is a greater sense of educational disadvantage amongst white working class pupils.  These point to the fact that local economic, historical and geographic factors take</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:14pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">precedence</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:14pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">over ethnicity as a precursor alone.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Is the problem of educational underachievement particularly worse for boys or girls?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">Overall, our small sample of respondents agreed with the idea that white working class girls attain higher levels of educational achievement than white working class boys. </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">However, a third of respondents also felt that there was no disparity in the levels of educational achievement between girls and boys. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">For those that felt that white working class boys suffered from greater levels of educational inequality compared to their female peers, the reasons given were varied. They included:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">Negative out of school activities were partly to blame and tended to have a greater influence on boys than they did on girls – specifically in relation to gangs, and other forms of anti-social behaviour outside of school.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">A lack of positive role models among white working class pupils and a shared assumption amongst boys that learning was not a high priority.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">Girls were often more likely to make a consistent effort throughout school compared to boys who often resigned themselves to poor performance past years 9 and 10.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">What steps can schools take to improve the educational outcomes and attainment of white working class pupils?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">In order to improve the educational outcomes and attainment of white working class pupils, the following recommendations were given by our respondents and participants based on their own individuals experiences: </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">Every vulnerable child should be provided with one adult in the school that is willing to champion them and encourage them to do better. This person would also be expected to coordinate high quality mutual engagement between the school and parent. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">Children should be provided with extra curricula activities in which success can be recognised. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">Schools should encourage white working class boys to collaborate with lower achieving girls so as to bring out their skills in leadership in order to help them stay focused and provide them with better learning opportunities. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">Greater emotional support should be provided, alongside more resources to support white working class pupils learning and mentoring schemes with positive role models that they can aspire to be like.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">There was also a general consensus that more targeted interventions should be implemented. These would be designed in a way that recognises the specific issues that white working class pupils face.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">In order to support schools with understanding what they can do to better understand the barriers that white working class pupils face, we also asked participants and ambassadors what them themselves would suggest as to what schools can do to better understand the needs of white working class pupils. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">To this question, respondents recommended:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">Schools facilitate greater communication with parents to try and gain a better sense of what their child’s specific interests are. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">Pupils should be provided with positive role models who can support them and act as a conduit between them and the school – ideally, someone that has themselves proved successful despite coming from a similar background. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">Instilling high aspirations, so pupils feel they can succeed, can enter university and access any profession, not matter their background. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">The greater use of intervention groups for students who have poor behaviour and aspirations. Recommendations included after school cooking classes or motivational speakers delivering certain sessions. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">Finally, it was also recommended that schools do more to actively engage with the communities that they serve – including the opportunity for parents to engage with the school outside of formal parental meetings.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">What role can government play in delivering improved educational outcomes for white working class pupils?</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">Participants and ambassadors were broadly in agreement as to what governments can do to improve educational outcomes for white working class pupils. Broadly speaking, these can be broken down into three key themes:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">1)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">More work to encourage white working class parents to have and support higher aspirations for their children – this included activities such as encouraging parents to read with their children and incentivising / requiring parents to attend parents’ evenings. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">2)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">More targeted support for children from white working class backgrounds – with incentives for schools to provide this activity</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">3)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">Encouraging a greater use of social and community capital amongst children from white working class pupils. Recommendations included stimulating the economy of areas that are typically home to children from white working class backgrounds in order to ensure that there are opportunities outside of school for young people. Support for youth services was highlighted, enabling </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">horizon-broadening opportunities and support for pupils outside of school/in holidays etc. Similarly, </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">the suggestion was made that the national curriculum should aim to utilise more of the social and community capital that white working class pupils have in order to give students’ education a sense of context, and a sense that school can benefit them despite the fact that their parents may not have been successful at school.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">Other recommendations from participants and ambassadors included: </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">Pupils should be provided with high quality information, advice and guidance in relation to higher and further education, as well as other vocational opportunities. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">School budgets remain consistent. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">A policy akin to EMA should be introduced in order to support pupils from low income backgrounds to remain in education until 18. </span></li></ul><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:1.5pt 1.5pt 1.5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">These recommendations reflect and recognise that white working class children are not a homogenous group.  </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">The challenges they face vary greatly and are often driven by geographical and economic factors, rather than ethnicity. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">For example, within London </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">almost half of London’s poorest white pupils get five good GCSEs with English and maths compared with the national average of 31% for white children on Free School Meals</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">Action to address underachievement therefore needs to be grounded in the local context – economic situations, levels of intergenerational poverty and access to services – and not purely focused on ethnicity. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">The performance of white working class children in inner-London reflects a broader advancement in the quality of schools and teaching within the capital. Over the last decade the capital’s schools have progressed from some of the country’s worst, to now being the second highest performing region – only behind outer-London. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">This change gives focus to the central importance of the quality of school teaching and leadership. We were unable to access Department for Education data </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">on</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt"> free school meal </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">attainment by </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">ethnicity</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt"> at a Local Authority level</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">so we were unable to assess how the balance varies around the country. Evidence, however, </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">suggests that many of the areas </span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">now struggling are rural and coastal communities. These communities tend to have a higher proportion of white working class communities as well as struggle in attracting talented teachers and leaders.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">Teach First’s experience has demonstrated the importance of policies that support the targeted recruitment, placement and development of high quality teachers and leaders in these areas. Whilst Teach First is expanding its work across the country and increasingly focusing on these communities, it is not the only means to achieve this outcome. All appropriate means to attract, train and retain the best teachers and leaders in the areas of highest need should be explored and welcomed. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:1.5pt 1.5pt 1.5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:1.5pt 1.5pt 1.5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Conclusion</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:1.5pt 1.5pt 1.5pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">In this response, we have brought together the individual responses of a small selection of our participants and ambassadors to outline some of the problems that they feel contribute considerably to educational inequality amongst white working class pupils. These views are their own and do not necessarily reflect the view of Teach First as an organisation itself. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">We have responded in this way as we recognise the diversity of educational inequality and the different experiences and views of our teachers. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">Indeed, if we are to properly tackle one of our country’s greatest tragedy’s, we believe that a collaborative effort across society is required – one that utilises the skills and expertise of as many people as possible. Despite significant inroads being made to tackle educational inequality and provide more young people with the education that they deserve, too many children are still falling behind. We therefore welcome this opportunity to showcase the experiences and recommendations of our participants and ambassadors, and hope that it will support the Education Select Committee’s work around supporting children from disadvantaged backgrounds. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">September 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Appendix</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span></p><h4 style="margin:10pt 0pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">Further information on Teach First</span></h4><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">Teach First is a charity with the vision that no child’s educational success is limited by their socio-economic background. It believes that the scale of change needed is so great it requires a movement of leaders to make a difference at a pupil, school and system level. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">Teach First is working towards achieving its vision by enabling its participants and ambassadors in the classroom to raise the achievement, aspiration, and access to opportunity of children from low socio-economic backgrounds, whilst developing a network of leaders with a life-long commitment to ending inequality in education from both inside and outside the classroom.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">Teach First currently operates in Wales and nine regions across England: London, West Midlands, East Midlands, Yorkshire the Humber, North West and the North East, South East, South Coast and the South West. In 2014 we will open our operations in the East of England.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">Trainees commit to a minimum of two years at their partner school, where they teach an Newly Qualified Teacher (NQT) timetable; and nearly three quarters choose to stay for at least a third year. Their 13 month Initial Teacher Training starts with the unique six-week Summer Institute which provides trainees with intensive preparation for teaching in their school. Trainees then complete both their PGCE training year and their first year as an NQT in their school.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">Teach First is raising the quality and profile of the teaching profession and has made teaching in schools in challenging circumstances one of the most prestigious options for top graduates. In 2013, Teach First was ranked 3rd in the coveted league of Times Top 100 Graduate Employers. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">Teach First has built a national reputation for collaborating with schools, local authorities and business partners to help close the attainment gap. Working in eight regions across England, it knows that placing inspirational teachers in schools in challenging circumstances for a minimum of two years drives improvement in standards and results.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Department for Education, </span><a href="http://www.education.gov.uk/researchandstatistics/statistics/allstatistics/a00219200/"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.education.gov.uk/researchandstatistics/statistics/allstatistics/a00219200/</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">, p5.  </span></p></body></html>